      "IsPublic": true,
      "FullName": "Sandbox.Physics.ControlJoint",
      "Name": "ControlJoint",
      "Attributes": [
        {
          "FullName": "DescriptionAttribute",
          "ConstructorArguments": [
            "The control joint is designed to control the movement of a body while remaining responsive to collisions. A spring can be used to control position and rotation, while a velocity motor can control velocity and simulate friction in top-down games. Both methods can be combined — for example, a spring with friction. Position and velocity control each have configurable force and torque limits."
          ]
        },
        {
          "FullName": "Sandbox.Internal.SourceLocationAttribute",
          "ConstructorArguments": [
            "Systems\\Physics\\Joints\\ControlJoint.cs",
            "9"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "Documentation": {
        "Summary": "The control joint is designed to control the movement of a body while remaining responsive to collisions.  \nA spring can be used to control position and rotation, while a velocity motor can control velocity and  \nsimulate friction in top-down games. Both methods can be combined — for example, a spring with friction.  \nPosition and velocity control each have configurable force and torque limits."
      },
      "DocId": "T:Sandbox.Physics.ControlJoint"
    },
